---+++ Classification resources
   * Stede, M., Umbach, C. (1998) !DiMLex: A lexicon of discourse markers for text generation and understanding
   * From connectives to argumentative markers (Tseronis 2011) 
      * interesting as a source of features, http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10503-011-9215-x
   * [[http://arxiv.org/abs/cs/0402057][Integrating Defeasible Argumentation and Machine Learning Techniques]]
      * -> classification
   * see table here: [[ArgumentMining.ArgumentExtraction]]
   * lexical features: [[ArgumentMining.HighSchoolMaterial]]
   * [[http://www.aaai.org/ocs/index.php/FLAIRS/FLAIRS12/paper/viewFile/4366/4806][Applying Kernel Methods to Argumentation Mining.]]
   * CharuC. Aggarwal and ChengXiang Zhai. A survey of text classification algorithms.Charu C. Aggarwal and ChengXiang Zhai, editors, Mining Text Data, pages 163222. Springer US, 2012. http://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4614-3223-4_6 (NotInBib)
   * Leo Breiman. Random forests. Mach. Learn., 45(1):532, October 2001. http://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A:1010933404324.pdf (NotInBib)
   * George Forman. An extensive empirical study of feature selection metrics for text classification. J. Mach. Learn. Res., 3:12891305, March 2003. http://machinelearning.wustl.edu/mlpapers/paper_files/Forman03.pdf (NotInBib)
   * Vaishali Ganganwar. An overview of classification algorithms for imbalanced datasets. International Journal of Emerging Technology and Advanced Engineering, 2:4247, 2012. (NotInBib)
   * Chih-Wei Hsu, Chih-Chung Chang, and Chih-Jen Lin. A practical guide to support vector classification. Technical report, Department of Computer Science, National Taiwan University, 2003.





